  "body": "\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.8.17`\r\nOS & Version: Linux\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\n`eth_syncing` should be `false` when a ropsten node is on the constantinople canonical head. \r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nThe nodes routinely consider themselves to be syncing even though they appear to be on the canonical head.\r\n\r\n```\r\n> eth.syncing\r\n{\r\n  currentBlock: 4230133,\r\n  highestBlock: 4230732,\r\n  knownStates: 57056208,\r\n  pulledStates: 57056208,\r\n  startingBlock: 4229984\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nMy theory is that `highestBlock` value is coming from a non-Constantinople node.  Is it possible that geth isn't rejecting the pre-fork chains when calculating `highestBlock`?\r\n \r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\nMonitor the status of `eth_syncing` on a ropsten node after the Constantinople block 4230000.\r\n\r\n\r\n",
